'''Mihail Lascăr''' ([[November 8]], [[1889]], [[Târgu Jiu]] &ndash; [[July 24]], [[1959]], [[Bucharest]]) was a [[Romania]]n General during [[World War II]], and [[Ministry of National Defense of Romania|Minister of Defense]] from 1946 to 1947. 

After graduating from the Infantry Officer School in 1910 with the rank of 2nd lieutenant, he fought in the [[Second Balkan War]] and in [[World War I]], being promoted to major. He became colonel in 1934, and brigadier general in 1939. 

On [[January 10]], [[1941]], he was appointed commanding officer of the First [[Vânători de Munte|Mountain Brigade]], an elite military unit of the [[Third Army (Romania)|Third Army]]. On [[June 22]], [[1941]],  [[Operation Barbarossa]] (the invasion of the [[Soviet Union]] by [[Nazi Germany]] and its allies) commenced, with the Mountain Brigade entering [[Bukovina|Northern Bukovina]].  From there,  Lascăr and his unit swung East, crossing the rivers [[Dniester]], [[Bug]], and [[Dnieper]]. He fought in the Battle of the [[Azov Sea]], and then in the [[Battle of Crimea (1941)|Battle of Crimea]], remaining in charge of the Mountain Brigade until [[February 10]], [[1942]]. On [[March 11]], [[1942]], he took charge of the 6th Division of the [[Third Army (Romania)|Romanian Third Army]], and fought at the [[Romanian Armies in the Battle of Stalingrad|Battle of Stalingrad]].  He was taken prisoner on [[November 22]], [[1942]], spending the years 1943-1945 in captivity in the Soviet Union. <!-- first at Kranogor, then at Suzdal and Ivanov, and finally at Camp 48, reserved for generals.-->

On [[April 12]], [[1945]], Lascăr became commander of the [[Horia, Cloşca şi Crişan Division]]; the [[political commissar]] attached to this Soviet-organized unit was the Communist activist [[Valter Roman]].  On [[September 12]], [[1945]], Lascăr was named commander of the [[Fourth Army (Romania)|Fourth Army]]. He was a leader of the Electoral Commission of the Army, in advance of the [[Romanian general election, 1946|general election]] of [[November 19]], [[1946]].  After a coalition led by the [[Romanian Communist Party]] won the election (through widespread intimidation tactics and electoral fraud), he was appointed Minister of Defense, staying in that post from [[November 29]], [[1946]] to [[December 27]], [[1947]], when he was replaced by [[Emil Bodnăraş]].  He was then Inspector of the [[Romanian Army|Armed Forces]] until [[January 12]], [[1950]], when he was discharged from active duty.

On [[June 7]], [[1947]], he signed the decree establishing the footbal club ''Asociaţia Sportivă a Armatei Bucureşti'', now [[FC Steaua Bucureşti]]. 

==Awards==
In January 1942, he received the German [[Iron Cross]], 1st class and the [[Knight's Cross of the Iron Cross|Knight's Cross]] with Oak Leaves (the first [[List of foreign recipients of the Knight's Cross with Oak Leaves|foreign recipient]] of this decoration).
 
On [[December 31]], [[1942]], he was decorated with the [[Order of Michael the Brave]], 2nd class.

